Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

I analyzed the movies dataset and communicated my findings about it. I used the Python libraries such as NumPy, pandas, and Matplotlib to make my analysis easier.

This data set contains information about over 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue for the movies. Certain columns, like cast and genres, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters. The final two columns ending with _adj show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time. I will be dropping some of these columsn later as I do not need them all for my analysis.

Description of the raw dataset columns:-¶

  • id - A unique identifier for each movie.
  • popularity - A numeric quantity specifying the movie popularity.
  • budget - The budget in which the movie was made.
  • revenue - The worldwide revenue generated by the movie.
  • original_title - The title of the movie before translation or adaptation.
  • cast - The name of lead and supporting actors.
  • homepage - A link to the homepage of the movie.
  • director - Movie Director
  • tagline - Movie's tagline.
  • overview - A brief description of the movie.
  • runtime - The running time of the movie in minutes.
  • genre - The genre of the movie, Action, Comedy ,Thriller etc.
  • production_companies - The production house of the movie.
  • release_date - The date on which it was released.
  • vote_count - the count of votes recieved.
  • vote_average - average ratings the movie recieved.
  • release_year - Movie release year
  • budget_adj - show the budget of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for
  • revenue_adj - show the revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for

Questions for Analysis:¶

1: What are the number of movies released each year?

2: Waht is the relationship between movie budget and revenue?

3: What is the most profitable movie?

4: What is the least profitable movie?

x = movies["budget_adj"]
y = movies["revenue_adj"]
correlation_movies = x.corr(y)
print(correlation_movies)

# add title to plot
plt.title('Correlation between Budget and Revenue')
# plotting the data
plt.scatter(x,y)

# This will fit the best line into the graph
plt.plot(np.unique(x), np.poly1d(np.polyfit(x, y, 1))
         (np.unique(x)), color='red')

# labelling axes
plt.xlabel('Budget')
plt.ylabel('Revenue')

0.524506836494574

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Budget and Revenue(USD)')

plt.legend(loc = 'upper right')

plt.show();

Observarions

  • The graph above shows the revenue remaining higher than the budget as the years go by, this further shows that they have a positively correlated relationship.

Observation

  • Star Wars is the movie with the Highest Profit. Showing that it is the most profitable in the dataset.
  • The Warrior's Way is the movie with the Lowest Profit (which actually made a great loss.

Conclusions¶

One: There has been a great significant increase in the number of movies released each year since 1960 up to 2015, judging from the increased seen in the visualization.

Two: The revenue of movies consistenty remained above the budget each year.

Three: Budget and Revenue have a positively correlated relationship. Through the succeeding years, the revenue was higher that the budget of movies.

Four: Star Wars made the most profit as the movie released in the dataset through year 1960 - 2015.

Five: The Warrior's Way made the least profit, in other words, it recorded the lowest profit in the entire dataset.

Limitations¶

One: The number of zeros in the columns I needed for my data analysis was much and quite an issue, so, I decided to keep all the zero values instead of dropping them from the dataset.So, I replaced the zero values in each column with NaN (not a number) and replace with mean values.

Two: I wasn't aure how exactly the vote_average and vote_count are calculated so I couldn't use them for my analysis, such as calculating movie rating over a time period (month/year).

Three: I also did not evaluate the 'budget' and 'revenue' columns with a particular currency like USD because it could be misguiding. This is because I saw that the dataset has a column for production_country, it could be possible that the budget and revenue was based on the country's currency or based on USD.
